### Nucleophilic Addition Reactions

* Due to the high electronegative of the O atom, and contribution of the dipolar resonance structure, the C=O bond of the carbonyl group is **highly polar**. The **partially positive carbonyl C atom (C3+)** acts as an **electron-deficient site**, which will be **attacked by a nucleophile**.
* Since the C of C=O is **unsaturated**, it can undergo **addition reaction** readily. Hence, carbonyl compounds (_i.e._ aldehydes & ketones) undergo **nucleophilic addition**.

